body:
1) The "force fallback to cpu" is actually an optimization wherein ORT dynamically decides that performing certain operations on CPU is more optimal than incurring the overhead of scheduling CUDA kernels and waiting for the operation to finish. Usually they are tiny "shape" related subgraphs whose result is ultimately needed on CPU (because shapes don't hold very large number of elements requiring GPUs to process them) . In your case:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9969784/112949791-771df400-90ee-11eb-97cb-af8acc467ee2.png)

The Shape output feeds through a simple `Gather` and `Equal` which forms the `condition` to the downstream `If` node (and the condition needs to be on CPU even if the `If` node itself is placed on CUDA) and hence ORT made the decision that processing a few shape dim values (Gather + Equal) on CPU is better than launching 2 CUDA kernels + waiting for it to finish + getting it back to CPU to ultimately feed into the `If` node. 

This is an optimization which is just getting logged. 

2) The runtime error is simple - your onnx model requires 3 inputs and you are feeding it just 1. Hence, the complaint from ORT.

Hope this answers your questions.
@hariharans29 `export_params=None` is wrong, but the model does not contain any parameters in fact. Why would it require 3 inputs?
very interesting, seems a PyTorch bug. I'll report it there

issue.title: Parameterless model still has extra inputs when exported to ONNX + insufficient checking of argument export_params

labels.name: triaged
labels.description: This issue has been looked at a team member, and triaged and prioritized into an appropriate module

repository.name: pytorch
repository.description: Tensors and Dynamic neural networks in Python with strong GPU acceleration

issue.body:
Note the wrong setting of `export_params = None` - probably should be checked by PyTorch to only be `True` or `False` (if `None` is accepted, its semantics should be clearly stated in the docs). Somehow the exported model has three inputs: one tensor and two int64. Where are they coming from?

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1041752/113300283-0baa7100-92fe-11eb-9f0e-8cd4edcdfe79.png)


Original report: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/7096 

```python
import onnxruntime
from torch import nn
import torch
import torch.nn.functional as F

print(torch.__version__)


class Model(nn.Module):
	def forward(self, x):
		p = F.pad(x, (1, 1), mode='constant').squeeze(1)
		return dict(o=p)


model = Model()
model.to(device='cuda')
x = torch.rand(1, 10).to(device='cuda')
print(x.shape)
print(model(x))

torch.onnx.export(
		model, (x,),
		'fp32_squeeze_repro.onnx',
		verbose=False,
		opset_version=12,
		export_params=None,
		do_constant_folding=True,
		input_names=['x'],
		output_names = ['o']
)

runtime = onnxruntime.InferenceSession('fp32_squeeze_repro.onnx')
print(runtime.run(None, dict(x=x.cpu().numpy())))

#1.8.0
#torch.Size([1, 10])
#{'o': tensor([[0.0000, 0.7245, 0.8421, 0.7092, 0.6501, 0.6383, 0.4523, 0.5001, 0.9790,
#         0.5590, 0.3269, 0.0000]], device='cuda:0')}
#Traceback (most recent call last):
#  File "fp32_squeeze_repro.py", line 33, in <module>
#    print(runtime.run(None, dict(x=x.cpu().numpy())))
#  File "/opt/conda/lib/python3.8/site-packages/onnxruntime/capi/onnxruntime_inference_collection.py", line 120, in run
#    raise ValueError("Model requires {} inputs. Input Feed contains {}".format(num_required_inputs, num_inputs))
#ValueError: Model requires 3 inputs. Input Feed contains 1
```

[fp32_squeeze_repro.onnx.zip](https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/files/6243797/fp32_squeeze_repro.onnx.zip)

issue.title: Force fallback to CPU execution for Gather, Unsqueeze, Concat nodes - onnxruntime-gpu 1.7.0, opset 12 and 13

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
We have two models. 
We exported them to onnx. 
We'd like to run them entirely on the GPU. 

We have encountered a lot of CPU fallbacks for the following types of nodes: 
Gather, Unsqueeze, Concat
for both opset_12 and opset_13. 
onnxruntime-gpu 1.7.0

onnx files and logs: 

modelA: 
https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1aJlnyp0P8z2-_58aQhv0zpd-4A_Vv3sC?usp=sharing

modelB:
https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1D7q4qvp5txX1FFT33TbHrX-qPC0aeqZd?usp=sharing

reproduction steps: 
`
docker run --rm -it --gpus=all --ipc=host --net=host -v /path/to/your/models:/data nvcr.io/nvidia/pytorch:21.03-py3 
`
within the container, type: 
`
pip install onnxruntime-gpu
`
now type
`ipython`
now, within ipython type: 
`import torch`
`import onnxruntime`
`sessionOptions = onnxruntime.SessionOptions()`
`sessionOptions.log_severity_level = 0`
`sess = onnxruntime.InferenceSession("modelA.onnx", sessionOptions)`
with opset_12 you'll see
```
Loading /data/modelA.onnx
Starting inference session for onnx model providers=None sess_options=<onnxruntime.capi.onnxruntime_pybind11_state.SessionOptions object at 0x7f17d22b56f0>
2021-05-19 10:44:10.409065555 [W:onnxruntime:Default, fallback_cpu_capability.cc:135 GetCpuPreferredNodes] Force fallback to CPU execution for node: Gather_12
```
we got a lot of such errors for the above mentioned nodes with opset_13, and with opset_12 and opset_13 for modelB. 

Please, find the complete error logs under the google drive links.
